body: @harupy are you sure you're on 1.9 and not master when you experience this issue? I would expect https://github.com/mlflow/mlflow/commit/4f576bbcb889275fda303fe531344ff6bb160c9d to be causing this issue (and it is not included in the 1.9 branch cut), and I currently have an in-progress UI PR that will fix this.

@harupy Confirmed this just now - installing mlflow 1.9.0 and running the UI doesn't show any error on the registered models page for me.

I'll track this issue in the UI PR and close when that merges. Thanks (and let me know if I'm missing some particular configuration here)!

FYI
When I'm doing this tutorial (https://www.mlflow.org/docs/latest/tutorials-and-examples/tutorial.html), I got same error on both 1.9.0 and 1.9.1.
This may be because of using file store backend.

In 1.9.1, I got a error message shown in browser console.
`" Model registry functionality is unavailable; got unsupported URI './mlruns' for model registry data storage. Supported URI schemes are: ['postgresql', 'mysql', 'sqlite', 'mssql']. See https://www.mlflow.org/docs/latest/tracking.html#storage for how to run an MLflow server against one of the supported backend storage locations."`
(This is generated by commit https://github.com/mlflow/mlflow/commit/8e7c94e0115d283fd98a70bfdfcb37713b4b66ff)

IMHO, if this models page doesn't expect to work with file store backend, showing that information make it more user-friendly in this case.

@cafeal It definitely makes sense to show an error message (instead of `something went wrong`) on the UI like below.

![Screen Shot 2020-06-29 at 17 32 53](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/17039389/85991591-9c31e900-ba2e-11ea-905a-3ac6fb0da95d.png)
That sounds like a better thing to do @harupy! If you end up making a PR for this soon, I'd be happy to review

The critical problem is that when I clicked `Models`, the entire application fails.
(e.g. If I clicked Experiments after it, it also shows `something went wrong`. could you reproduce this in your environment? @harupy )
So, IMO, this UI should handle this 400 error correctly as not just showing up an error message.

rename.from: [BUG] Error when opening the registered-models page on the UI
rename.to: [BUG] Error when opening the registered-models page on the UI due to a file store backend
